    buyerGuidance: `Boundaries are a common source of post-completion disputes. They matter because they define your property's extent and your maintenance responsibility. The TA6 deliberately separates what you can see (fence, hedge, wall) from what the title says (title plan and deeds about ownership) because these often disagree and create risk. As you read the answers: (1) Are all four sides accounted for--front, back, left, right? The seller should have a clear answer for each, even if it's "don't know". (2) Are there mismatches between physical features and legal title--a fence moved over time, a hedge drifted into the neighbour's plot? These can usually be lived with, but they signal potential future disputes. Ask your solicitor to review the title plan for "T-marks" (denoting legal boundary responsibility) and whether any boundary agreements are registered.`,
