    buyerGuidance: `This section covers alterations and building works done to the property, planning permission and building regulation issues, guarantees and warranties for new work, and environmental matters (flooding, radon, contamination, knotweed). These matter because they affect the property's condition, your legal protection if something goes wrong, your insurance, and your ability to sell or extend in future. As you read through, focus on three things: (1) What has been built? Extensions, lofts, new kitchens, bathrooms, rewires, boilers, solar panels. (2) Were the proper permissions and certificates obtained? Planning permission, building control sign-off, FENSA certificates for electrical work, Gas Safe certification, etc. (3) Are there guarantees? New kitchens, boilers, structural work, and installations often come with guarantees (NHBC, LABC, manufacturer's warranty) that protect you if something fails. Your lender will want to know about major works and their certification. Ask your solicitor to raise enquiries about any work done, to obtain copies of all consents and certificates, and to clarify what guarantees exist and for how long.`,
