    buyerGuidance: `This section addresses environmental factors affecting the property: radon gas, Japanese knotweed, ground contamination, coal mining subsidence, and flood risk. These are location-based factors unlikely to change, so understanding them before purchase is essential. They affect property value, insurability, mortgageability, and your enjoyment of the property. As you read through, focus on identifying risks specific to the property's location. Radon in highrisk postcodes, knotweed if near waterways or in known-affected areas, subsidence if in mining areas or on clay soils, and flooding if near rivers or low-lying. Past flooding or damage should be clearly explained and remedial measures evident. Contamination or ground instability significantly affects long-term enjoyment and cost. These factors are often location-based and permanent, so don't ignore them. They directly affect your insurance cost and the property's future saleability. Ask your surveyor whether any environmental risks are evident. Ask your solicitor to obtain official searches showing flood risk, radon, mining, and contamination status.`,
